Note:
MAC ADDRESS - 48-bit EUI-48 Media Access Control Address (Tier 1)

Implements the MACAddress value type per IEEE 802 (Standard for Local and
Metropolitan Area Networks: Overview and Architecture) and IEEE 802-2014
which defines the 48-bit EUI-48 address format historically known as
"MAC address."

Representation:
  A MAC address is 48 bits packed into a Runa Integer (64-bit storage).
  Octet 0 is the most-significant byte ("AA" in "AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF").

  Bit layout (most-significant first):
    bit 47..40 : octet 0  (OUI byte 1)
    bit 39..32 : octet 1  (OUI byte 2)
    bit 31..24 : octet 2  (OUI byte 3)
    bit 23..16 : octet 3  (NIC byte 1)
    bit 15..8  : octet 4  (NIC byte 2)
    bit 7..0   : octet 5  (NIC byte 3)

  Special bits in octet 0:
    bit 0 (least-significant) = I/G bit (Individual=0, Group=1 / multicast)
    bit 1                     = U/L bit (Universal=0, Local=1)

Text formats accepted (RFC 7042, IEEE 802 conventions):
  - Colon-separated  : "AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF"  (Linux / IETF)
  - Hyphen-separated : "AA-BB-CC-DD-EE-FF"  (Windows / IEEE 802.1)
  - Cisco dot-quad   : "AABB.CCDD.EEFF"     (Cisco IOS)

Output format is selectable via to_string(format) where format is:
  - MAC_FORMAT_COLON  (default)
  - MAC_FORMAT_HYPHEN
  - MAC_FORMAT_CISCO

OUI registry lookup is provided as the 24-bit prefix (first three octets).
RFC 7042 references the IEEE OUI database for vendor identification.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/string_builder.runa" as SB
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/char_core.runa" as Char

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let MAC_BYTES be 6
Let MAC_BITS be 48
Let MAC_OCTET_MAX be 255
Let MAC_MAX_VALUE be 281474976710655
Let MAC_FORMAT_COLON be 0
Let MAC_FORMAT_HYPHEN be 1
Let MAC_FORMAT_CISCO be 2

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Build a MAC address from six octets. Octet 0 is most-significant. Each
octet is validated against 0..255 to prevent silent wrap-around when
packing into the integer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Pack:
  result = (o0 * 2^40) + (o1 * 2^32) + (o2 * 2^24) + (o3 * 2^16) + (o4 * 2^8) + o5
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1). Six range checks plus five additions.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Octet range validation prevents bit-pattern corruption that would alter
the I/G and U/L flags read by classification predicates.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_from_octets" takes o0 as Integer, o1 as Integer, o2 as Integer, o3 as Integer, o4 as Integer, o5 as Integer returns Integer:
    If o0 is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o0 is greater than MAC_OCTET_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o1 is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o1 is greater than MAC_OCTET_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o2 is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o2 is greater than MAC_OCTET_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o3 is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o3 is greater than MAC_OCTET_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o4 is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o4 is greater than MAC_OCTET_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o5 is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If o5 is greater than MAC_OCTET_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let part_0 be o0 multiplied by 1099511627776
    Let part_1 be o1 multiplied by 4294967296
    Let part_2 be o2 multiplied by 16777216
    Let part_3 be o3 multiplied by 65536
    Let part_4 be o4 multiplied by 256
    Let result be part_0 plus part_1
    Set result to result plus part_2
    Set result to result plus part_3
    Set result to result plus part_4
    Set result to result plus o5
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Extract octet (0..5) from a MAC address. Octet 0 is most-significant.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Divide-and-modulo decomposition with bounds check.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on bad index so callers distinguish error from 0 octet.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_get_octet" takes addr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If addr is greater than MAC_MAX_VALUE:
        Return -1
    End If
    If index is equal to 0:
        Return addr divided by 1099511627776
    End If
    If index is equal to 1:
        Let r be addr modulo by 1099511627776
        Return r divided by 4294967296
    End If
    If index is equal to 2:
        Let r be addr modulo by 4294967296
        Return r divided by 16777216
    End If
    If index is equal to 3:
        Let r be addr modulo by 16777216
        Return r divided by 65536
    End If
    If index is equal to 4:
        Let r be addr modulo by 65536
        Return r divided by 256
    End If
    If index is equal to 5:
        Return addr modulo by 256
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HEX PARSING HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Convert a single hex digit to its integer value 0..15. Accepts upper and
lower case (case-insensitive parsing per RFC 7042).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Range tests on '0'..'9', 'a'..'f', 'A'..'F'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on invalid digit.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_hex_value" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return ch minus 48
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return ch minus 87
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return ch minus 55
        End If
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

@Reasoning
Convert an integer 0..15 to its uppercase ASCII hex digit. MAC addresses
are conventionally uppercase per IEEE 802 documentation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
0..9 -> '0'..'9', 10..15 -> 'A'..'F'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on out-of-range input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_hex_digit_char" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is greater than 15:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is less than 10:
        Return value plus 48
    End If
    Return value plus 55
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRING PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Parse a textual MAC address in any of the three accepted formats. The
format is auto-detected from the input shape: 17 characters with ':' or
'-' separators every two hex digits, or 14 characters with '.' separators
every four hex digits (Cisco form).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Inspect the length to dispatch to colon/hyphen or Cisco branches.
Walk through hex pairs, validating digit set and separator placement.
On success, return the packed 48-bit integer; on any malformation, -1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) where n is up to 17. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict validation prevents mis-parses of partial or padded input that
could allow spoofed device-identity claims.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_from_string" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    If length is equal to 17:
        Note: Colon or hyphen format.
        Let sep be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, 2
        If sep is not equal to 58:
            If sep is not equal to 45:
                Return -1
            End If
        End If
        Let octets be proc allocate from Layout with 48
        If octets is equal to 0:
            Return -1
        End If
        Let parse_failed be 0
        Let oi be 0
        While oi is less than 6:
            If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                Let base be oi multiplied by 3
                Let hi_pos be base
                Let lo_pos be base plus 1
                Let h_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, hi_pos
                Let l_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, lo_pos
                Let hv be proc mac_hex_value with h_ch
                Let lv be proc mac_hex_value with l_ch
                If hv is less than 0:
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                End If
                If lv is less than 0:
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                End If
                If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                    Let oct be (hv multiplied by 16) plus lv
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with octets, oi multiplied by 8, oct
                    If oi is less than 5:
                        Let sep_pos be base plus 2
                        Let sep_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, sep_pos
                        If sep_ch is not equal to sep:
                            Set parse_failed to 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            Set oi to oi plus 1
        End While
        If parse_failed is equal to 1:
            proc deallocate from Layout with octets
            Return -1
        End If
        Let o0 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 0
        Let o1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 8
        Let o2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 16
        Let o3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 24
        Let o4 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 32
        Let o5 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 40
        proc deallocate from Layout with octets
        Return proc mac_from_octets with o0, o1, o2, o3, o4, o5
    End If
    If length is equal to 14:
        Note: Cisco dot format AABB.CCDD.EEFF.
        Let dot1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, 4
        Let dot2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, 9
        If dot1 is not equal to 46:
            Return -1
        End If
        If dot2 is not equal to 46:
            Return -1
        End If
        Let octets be proc allocate from Layout with 48
        If octets is equal to 0:
            Return -1
        End If
        Let positions be proc allocate from Layout with 48
        If positions is equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with octets
            Return -1
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with positions, 0, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with positions, 8, 2
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with positions, 16, 5
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with positions, 24, 7
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with positions, 32, 10
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with positions, 40, 12
        Let parse_failed be 0
        Let oi be 0
        While oi is less than 6:
            If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with positions, oi multiplied by 8
                Let h_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, pos
                Let l_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, pos plus 1
                Let hv be proc mac_hex_value with h_ch
                Let lv be proc mac_hex_value with l_ch
                If hv is less than 0:
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                End If
                If lv is less than 0:
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                End If
                If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                    Let oct be (hv multiplied by 16) plus lv
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with octets, oi multiplied by 8, oct
                End If
            End If
            Set oi to oi plus 1
        End While
        proc deallocate from Layout with positions
        If parse_failed is equal to 1:
            proc deallocate from Layout with octets
            Return -1
        End If
        Let o0 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 0
        Let o1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 8
        Let o2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 16
        Let o3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 24
        Let o4 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 32
        Let o5 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with octets, 40
        proc deallocate from Layout with octets
        Return proc mac_from_octets with o0, o1, o2, o3, o4, o5
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FORMATTING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Render the address in one of the three canonical text formats. Output is
always uppercase. Format selection lets callers match downstream tool
expectations (IETF, IEEE, or Cisco IOS).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Decompose into six octets. For each octet append two uppercase hex digits.
Insert separator characters based on format selector.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - output is 14 or 17 bytes plus null terminator.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No untrusted input; output only. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_to_string" takes addr as Integer, format as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If addr is greater than MAC_MAX_VALUE:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If sb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 6:
        Let oct be proc mac_get_octet with addr, i
        Let high_nibble be oct divided by 16
        Let low_nibble be oct modulo by 16
        Let h_ch be proc mac_hex_digit_char with high_nibble
        Let l_ch be proc mac_hex_digit_char with low_nibble
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, h_ch
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, l_ch
        If format is equal to MAC_FORMAT_CISCO:
            If i is equal to 1:
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 46
            End If
            If i is equal to 3:
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 46
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If i is less than 5:
                If format is equal to MAC_FORMAT_HYPHEN:
                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 45
                Otherwise:
                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 58
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with sb
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The U/L (Universal/Local) bit is bit 1 of octet 0. When 0 the address is
assigned by IEEE through the OUI registry; when 1 it is locally
administered (RFC 7042 section 2.1.1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Test bit 1 of octet 0: (o0 / 2) modulo 2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Locally administered addresses do not carry vendor accountability and may
indicate spoofing in environments expecting only OUI-assigned hardware.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_is_universal" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let o0 be proc mac_get_octet with addr, 0
    Let ul_bit be (o0 divided by 2) modulo by 2
    If ul_bit is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
The I/G (Individual/Group) bit is bit 0 of octet 0. When 0 the frame is
addressed to a single station; when 1 it is multicast or broadcast.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Test bit 0 of octet 0: o0 modulo 2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Unicast filtering at the L2 forwarding layer relies on this bit.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_is_unicast" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let o0 be proc mac_get_octet with addr, 0
    Let ig_bit be o0 modulo by 2
    If ig_bit is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
The broadcast address FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF per IEEE 802.3 directs frames to
every station on the segment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Compare to MAC_MAX_VALUE (all 48 bits set).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Broadcast frames bypass unicast filtering; switches use this distinction.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_is_broadcast" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to MAC_MAX_VALUE:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OUI EXTRACTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Return the 24-bit Organizationally Unique Identifier (OUI) which is the
first three octets of the MAC address per IEEE 802. The OUI identifies
the manufacturer assigned through the IEEE Registration Authority.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
oui = addr / 2^24 (extract upper 24 bits).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Used by network management tools to assert vendor expectations.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mac_oui" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If addr is greater than MAC_MAX_VALUE:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return addr divided by 16777216
End Process
